03881nam a22006735i 9780804798150DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015028116  a97808047981507 a10.1515/97808047981502doi  a(DE-B1597)564703  a(OCoLC)1178769435  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aNX550.B4bS73 2016 4aNX550.B4bS73 2016 7aART0090002bisacsh04a709.04/062223  aGM 16122rvk0(DE-625)rvk/41787:1 aStavrinaki, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDada Presentism :bAn Essay on Art and History /cMaria Stavrinaki. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (120 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. ORLANDO -- tI. POSTHISTORY AND PREHISTORY -- tII. THE PRESENT AS REPRODUCIBLE TIME -- tIII. ART'S EFFICACY OR DADA'S USE VALUE -- tIV. THE MOMENT OF DECISION -- tV. THE PARADIGM OF IMMACULATE CONCEPTION -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDada is often celebrated for its strategies of shock and opposition, but in Dada Presentism, Maria Stavrinaki provides a new picture of Dada art and writings as a lucid reflection on history and the role of art within it. The original (Berlin-based) Dadaists' acute historical consciousness and their modern experience of time, she contends, anticipated the formulations of major historians such as Reinhart Koselleck and, more recently, François Hartog. The book explores Dada temporalities and concepts of history in works of art, artistic discourse, and in the photographs of the Berlin Dada movement. These photographs-including the famous one of the First International Dada Fair-are presented not as simple, transparent documents, but as formal deployments conforming to a very concrete theory of history. This approach allows Stavrinaki to link Dada to more contemporary artistic movements and practices interested in history and the archive. At the same time, she investigates what seems to be a real oxymoron of the movement: its simultaneous claim to the ephemeral and its compulsive writing of its own history. In this way, Dada Presentism also interrogates the limits between history and fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aArts and history. 0aArts, Moderny20th century. 0aDadaismzGermanyzBerlin. 4aArt and Politics. 4aAvant-Garde. 4aDada. 4aDecisionism. 4aMimesis. 4aPresentism. 4aPrimitivism. 4aReproducibility. 4aSemantic History. 4aTemporality. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479815040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798150.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles